314":"4 december 1314","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1277":"1277","1342":"1342","about 1277":"circa 1277","about 1310":"circa 1310","about 1289":"circa 1289","Battle of Bannockburn, England":"England","Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England":"Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England","Tonbridge, Kent, England":"Tonbridge, Kent, England","Haudlo, Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1277–4 December 1314":"about 1277–4 December 1314","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1270–1346":"1270–1346","1288–1314":"1288–1314","1314–1342":"1314–1342","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1250–1289":"1250–1289","24 June 1314":"24 June 1314","Abt 1314":"about 1314","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","4 December 1314":"4 December 1314","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1277":"1277","1342":"1342","about 1277":"about 1277","about 1310":"about 1310","about 1289":"about 1289","Battle of Bannockburn, England":"England","Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England":"Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England","Tonbridge, Kent, England":"Tonbridge, Kent, England","Haudlo, Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":13,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan FitzNigel was born about 1277, in Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England as the daughter of John FitzNigel. She married John Lovell 2nd Lord Lovel about 1310, in Hadlow, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She died on 4 December 1314, in Kent, England, at the age of 38."},"et":{"about 1277–4 December 1314":"umbes 1277–4. detsember 1314","1277–1314":"1277–1314","1270–1346":"1270–1346","1288–1314":"1288–1314","1314–1342":"1314–1342","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1250–1289":"1250–1289","24 June 1314":"24. juuni 1314","Abt 1314":"umbes 1314","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","4 December 1314":"4. detsember 1314","1346":"1346","1289":"1289","1288":"1288","1277":"1277","1342":"1342","about 1277":"umbes 1277","about 1310":"umbes 1310","about 1289":"umbes 1289","Battle of Bannockburn, England":"England","Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, England":"Boarstall, Buckinghamshire, 